Ireland has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Ireland, see Return to the UK
Travel
The availability of transport from Ireland to Great Britain is subject to change. Flights and ferry services continue to operate between Ireland and Great Britain. Some flight operators have announced that they are operating a reduced service. If you’re visiting Ireland, you should closely monitor public announcements regarding the scheduling of flight and ferry services, and be prepared to adjust your travel plans accordingly.
All arrivals from overseas, including Irish residents, are asked to self-isolate for 14 days on arrival. This does not apply to those returning to Ireland from Northern Ireland, nor to those who are briefly stopping over at an airport on their way to another country, nor to specified categories of essential supply chain workers such as aircrew, hauliers, maritime staff whether Irish-based or foreign-based.
Passengers on air and sea routes into Ireland are asked to complete a health passenger locator form providing the address of where they will self-isolate for the next 14 days and contact details for follow up. Details of passengers’ state of health are not requested. Individuals may be subject to spot checks by telephone after arrival to verify their compliance with these requirements.
Local measures
The Irish Government have introduced measures to combat the spread of coronavirus. On 18 May, Ireland moved to Phase 1 of a roadmap for easing lockdown restrictions. You are advised to stay at home as much as possible and avoid unnecessary journeys, except for the following 5 reasons:
To go to work, if your place of work is open and you cannot work from home
To shop for items you need
To exercise within 5km of your home
For medical reasons or to care for others
To meet friends or family outside, within 5km of your home, in groups of no more than
For full details please visit the Irish Government news service website
Shielding, or cocooning, remains in place for everyone over 70 and categories who are particularly vulnerable to COVID-19. Those cocooning may go outside for a short walk or a drive, within 5km of their home,whilst keeping to the social distancing guidelines. [Ireland’s transport network and services continue to operate safely and effectively, providing vital connectivity for essential workers and essential trade. The Irish Government recommends wearing a cloth face covering in situations where it is difficult to practise social distancing, for example, in shops or on busy public transport. More detailed guidance from the Irish Government on the safe use of face coverings can be found on the Irish Government website.
A link to all of the latest Irish Government guidance can be viewed on the Irish Government website.
Further information
Further information from the Irish Government on all recommended measures and updates regarding the situation in Ireland can be found on the Irish Government website.
If you’re travelling to Ireland, follow the advice of the Health Service Executive and the Health Protection Surveillance Centre and keep up to date with the regular updates on the situation from the Irish Government.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
You can find more information about cases in Ireland on the TravelHealthPro country page.
